tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe publication of this book honours Professor Carole Hillenbrand's outstanding achievements in and service to Islamic and Middle Eastern Scholarship.It gathers original research from a range of leading international scholars from the UK, Europe and the USA whose chapters throw new light on a set of topics in medieval Islamic history, Islamic doctrine and practice, and the interaction between Islam and the modern world. Seeking to present fresh evidence and engaging ways of looking at old and new material, the authors contribute to a richer understanding of the interaction between historical events, social trends, religious practices and lived experiences in medieval Turkey and Central Asia, Iran and the Arabic-speaking lands. The book also discusses how some of the most abiding themes in the Arab-Islamic tradition continue to resonate in the modern world. The book features contributions from: Julia Bray, Edmund Bosworth, Farhad Daftary, Gerhard Endress, Gary Leiser, Remke Kruk, Charles Melville, A. H. Morton, Ian Netton, Andrew Newman, A. Kevin Reinhart and Yasir Suleiman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aIslam and culture. 0aIslamxHistory. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh1 aBosworth, C. Edmund, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBray, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaftary, Farhad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEddé, Anne-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKruk, Remke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLe